reviews.text: Great big spaces with the option of power and water, water alone or no power and water sites. Amenities are clean and plenty of rubbish bins around.
Good day out for a family
Very interesting.
Great weekend
You have to go once in your life time to this race
20+ years and just keeps getting better.
A truly great experience.  Well organised for competitors and spectators alike.  One tough race, in superb scenery.  Do it, or watch it - just get out there
getting ready for a great fink race

The tour guide gives a great presentation with all of the different animals. The lizards were interesting. I'm not the biggest fan of snakes, but we were goven the chance to hold one. The group also got up close and personal with a crocodile and several more reptiles. Highly recommended for the adventurous traveller!

We were there when the snakes were fed. That was really interesting. You can see the the most poisonous snakes. If you would they explain you what you should do and how to apply a bandage in case of a snake-bit. 
But the animals have not so much free space  in the terrarium.
Very informative staff. Lots of snakes and lizards. Worth a visit

Really enjoyed this. The place is not very big, but they have a respectable collection of amphibians, including a large saltwater crocodile named Terry. They also have thorny devils, which were interesting to me as a non-australian. Make sure you are there in time for the demonstrations as you will be able to hold several reptiles including a snake. Staff were very nice. They have a nice little gift shop as well.

A little smaller than other reptile centres but in saying that it without a lot of people around we were able to hold the reptiles and be a little more interactive which was worth it. The staff were great and very knowledgeable !

This continues to be a highlight of any trip to Alice.  I’ve been there many times: the first time in its embryonic stages.  But every time I visit it’s through new eyes.
The introduction movie plays hourly in the cinema.  It gives you a good grounding on just what you’ll experience.  And of course like all good movies it has a great ending.
We then watched the Birds of Prey show in the amphitheatre.  Who says you shouldn’t work with kids or animals? The shod was like a well-oiled machine and the birds were the stars.
An easy walk takes you through the three main desert habitats, and you see the relevant wildlife and plants.  And it’s an indication of how well laid-out it is, that you don’t see the buildings at the entrance/exit until you’re on top of them.
The only downside is that the cafe is in the process of changing hands, and there wasn’t much food available for those who’s tummies were grumbling at lunch time.
A wonderful experience for all ages.

Parks like this around the world seem to be ten a penny. 
Don't let that thought put you off, this park certainly breaks that idea wide open and puts many, many others into the shade. 
From the genuinely warm and friendly welcome at the front desk until walking out the gate this is an excellent experience.
We started at 9 with the film show which has an awesome finale. (sorry no spoilers) We then watched the 10am show in the amphitheatre. Again, sorry no spoilers, a REAL must see! Entertaining and educational. We then wandered taking in the various desert zones beautifully recreated so naturally.
Spend time in the aquarium and excellent nocturnal house, you won't be disappointed.
Definitely a must see while in Alice.

Great animal park. The Free Flight Birds show is a must. The second must see is the nocturnal animals, wait until your eyes adjust to the dark and you'll be rewarded with many animals in they're natural habitat. There's guided tours as well. Easy walking paths for a pleasant experience.

Loved this park. It had a great setup, and I can tell they care for their animals. The staff were very accommodating, and the guided tours and displays throughout the day were great. Most of the entertainment of this park relies on their guided tours throughout the day. This is a great place to spend an entire day at. Enjoy!

This is such a great place. Its my favourite part of coming to Alice Springs. The bird show and all the animals are amazing. Will be coming back again when I come back to Alice. And the cafe food was very good and surprisingly the coffee tasted really good.

A historical building right in town. Has a lot of photos of the past and history. Royalty has stayed here. This was the Spring Flower Show and they had the CWA serving Devonshire tea, which they do once a month.

This is a great spot to visit if you are travelling through Alice springs. You can ride or walk out there from the centre of town if you are physically able, but avoid doing this if the weather is changing in September and October due to heat and snakes. The tours are run efficiently and there is plenty of history behind the station. Recommended from a keen traveller!

A fascinating glimpse into a vital part of our history so many are unaware of.  The buildings and contents are stunningly preserved, and the interpretation boards informative and clear.
My only gripe, and it’s a small one, is the distance to the car park.  It was 38 degrees the day we visited.  We chose to go to the telegraph station as it would be something low-intensity to do on such a day.  But by the time we walked to the entrance we were already spent.  There’s a drop-off point for coaches and cars to save some people the trek. It would be just nicer if there were a few parks closer.  On the really hot days there are less people, so surely it wouldn’t hurt.
But still thought it a must-see in Alice.

It's pretty bogus that they've carved out a private concession within the national park which charges a separate admission for which national park passes aren't valid. Moreover, not a lot to see, lots of flies. The trail back to town along the river is pretty, though... no admission required.

The day was extremely hot.  The guide gave informative commentary on each of the displays and told of the development of the places the telegraph and the water.  His knowledge of the facility and the original owners was outstanding. This is an excellently presented lesson in a valuable area of Australian history.
Well worth the time to visit and look around great area to start bile ride into town or start a walk from, nice picnic area and coffee shop
Fantastic museum. Definitely a must visit when in Alice springs. A large diverse range of old trucks on display with a lot of outback history behind them.

Its nice to camp, bus, caravan or stay here. It is a family place and most reasonable rate in Alice but not your typical 'caravan park' because it isn't one, its a transport museum which is pretty cool in itself and the people are very nice so it doesnt matter I'm not that into trucks but they are amazing in the Kenworth Hall and I like the cafe and gardens and kids train. A lot of people say they could stay longer because they must be very interested in transport history. Overall I very much like it here.
A great day, such a experience, beautiful trucks and machinery, hours well spent looking around, deprecated volunteers, to talk to.

Love love loved it 
Hope it doesn't close I still have so much to explore the place is huge
If you love trucks, you cannot go past this place.

Come here for possibly the best view of Alice  Springs. I recommend coming for sundown which looks stunning. I came back at night which was great aswell. You can drive up or do a short walk up a hill to get there. Might be a few people around depending on what time of year you come.

A must-visit during any Alice Springs holiday.  See the whole of the town laid out before you, including the Gap and the ranges rolling away into the distance.  Sunset from the hill is always a highlight, and if you’re there at the right time the Dawn Service on Anzac Day is intensely moving.

Great place to look over the city and to learn about our history. Would recommend walking down the rock stairs (looking towards town) to see a different view. Watch out for the flies though, they are everywhere!

What a beautiful spot to get the best views of Alice Springs. Go in the early morning or at sunset, even consider having a picnic here. See the Gap and the Ranges and the whole pretty town all from here.
Great views and good ANZAC info. I do ofter wonder if Aussies know what the acronym ANZAC means.
Most pleasant place nice an quite great staff an no body harassing anyone for smokes or money more locals should go there for peace

Best place in town, eco friendly, fresh produce, organic, plenty of options for those who have certain preferences or dietary requirements etc. A quiet and relaxed place to sit and enjoy your meal, great value for Alice.
Great place for a quiet, early morning cuppa outside with the birds.

Lovely place to sit ,eat and refresh after walking through the Botanical Gardens , with birdlife all around to watch(inside and outside dinning) .Great food ,drinks and all meals on the menu can be made Gluten Free !! Staff were very busy but that didn't change their happy mood and were eager to help you in the gifts section. Just Fab!!
Best breakfast ever! Superb coffee! Perfect setting!
